{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No disambiguation needed; instead note the intentional Kantian resonance in the Chinese term",
    "content": "**No standalone disambiguation TN. But a brief note acknowledging the resonance is warranted.**\n\nThe average philosophically literate English reader will not confuse mathematical category theory with Kantian categories. \"Category theory\" is well-established as a branch of mathematics; the notation (objects, morphisms, functors) makes the mathematical sense immediately obvious. A \"not to be confused with\" note would be patronizing.\n\nHowever, the author says the overlap is *intentional*. That is worth noting --- not as a disambiguation but as a philosophical observation. Something like:\n\n> \"Category theory (范畴论) --- a branch of mathematics concerned with structures and their transformations. The Chinese term 范畴 also translates Kant's *Kategorien* (categories of the understanding); the author's use of category theory to describe the structures of experience is a deliberate echo of this Kantian project, though the method is mathematical rather than transcendental.\"\n\nThis tells the reader something they would not know otherwise (the Chinese term bridges both senses, and the author is aware of this), rather than warning them against a confusion they were unlikely to make."
  }
}
